  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(28) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Thou shalt not revile the gods.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The LXX. And Vulgate give the passage this sense; and so it was understood, or at any rate expounded, by Philo (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "De Vit. Mos. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "ii. 26) and Josephus (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant. Jud. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "iv. 8, § 10), who boasted that the Jews abstained from reviling the gods of the nations. But the practice of the most pious Israelites in the best times was different (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 18:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 115:4-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 135:15-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 41:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 44:9-20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 10:11-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.). The gods of the heathen were uniformly, and with the utmost scorn. “reviled.” It has been suggested that the true meaning of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "elohim ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "in this place is “judges” (Rosenmüller, Zunz, Herxheimer); but to have that sense, the word requires the article. It is best, therefore, to translate by “God,” as is done by De Wette, Knobel, Keil, Kalisch, Canon Cook, &c., and to understand the entire passage as intended to connect the sin of cursing a ruler with that of reviling God, the ruler being regarded as God’s representative.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
